  "prompt": "What are Some interesting facts of Langar at golden temple?",
  "response": "The Langar at the Golden Temple in Amritsar, Punjab, India, is renowned for its scale, inclusivity, and the spirit of selfless service. Here are some interesting facts about it:\n\n1. **Largest Free Kitchen**: The Langar at the Golden Temple is one of the largest free kitchens in the world. It serves an estimated 50,000 to 100,000 people daily, and during special religious events, the number can go up significantly.\n\n2. **Inclusivity**: The concept of Langar embodies the principles of equality and community service. Everyone, regardless of caste, creed, religion, gender, or social status, is welcome to partake in the meal.\n\n3. **Volunteer-Driven**: The kitchen is primarily managed by volunteers, known as 'sevadars'. These volunteers come from diverse backgrounds and contribute their time and effort to prepare, cook, serve, and clean.\n\n4. **Simple Vegetarian Menu**: The meals served in the Langar are simple, wholesome, and vegetarian. The typical menu includes dal (lentils), roti (Indian bread), sabzi (vegetable curry), and kheer (sweet rice pudding).\n\n5. **Self-Sustaining**: The Langar operates through donations, both in terms of money and food supplies, provided by devotees. The system is highly organized, ensuring a continuous and efficient flow of resources.\n\n6. **Eco-Friendly Practices**: Efforts are made to reduce waste and promote eco-friendly practices. For example, traditional steel plates and utensils are used to minimize disposable waste, and solar panels have been installed to generate energy for the kitchen.\n\n7. **Historical Significance**: The tradition of Langar was established by Guru Nanak, the founder of Sikhism, and it has been continued by successive Sikh Gurus. It is a cornerstone of Sikh practice, emphasizing community service and humility.\n\n8. **Community Bonding**: The Langar fosters a sense of community and unity among those who partake in it. Sharing a meal sitting on the floor, side by side, reinforces the idea of equality and brotherhood.\n\nThese aspects make the Langar at the Golden Temple not only a remarkable logistical feat but also a profound embodiment of Sikh values and community spirit.",
